Before we get to counting in earnest, I want to discuss one fairly easy counting technique. If you learn nothing else from this lesson, I hope you will try and use this technique. The technique has to do with counting trumps and other long suits you may have as declarer. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

Many people try to count trumps by figuring out how many have been played. So, if they play one round, and everyone follows they say "four have been played." Then if they play another round, and say one defender doesn't follow, they think "seven have been played." But that can get very complicated, particularly if you as declarer or one of the defenders has ruffed a trick.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

A much easier way to keep track of trumps, or any long suit, is to just remember how many are out in the defenders hand. So, if you start with an 8-card fit, then there are five out in the two defensive hands. If you play one round, and both follow, then just remember there are three out. It is much easier to do it this way, as you are keeping track of fewer cards and numbers. You simply remember how many are out. Let me load an example hand to show you. |
